on |author-link2=Simon Jenkins |date=1984 |title=The battle for the Falklands |publisher=Norton |isbn=978-0-393-30198-4 |url=https://archive.org/details/battleforfalklan00hast_0 }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Hobson |first1=Chris |first2=Andrew |last2=Noble |editor1-last=Munro |editor1-first=Bob |date=2002 |title=Falklands air war |publisher=North American trade distribution, Specialty Press Publishers & Wholesalers |isbn=978-1-85780-126-2 }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Hunt |first1=Rex |author-link1=Rex Masterman Hunt |date=1992 |title=My Falkland Days |publisher=Politico's Publishing |isbn=978-1-84275-017-9 }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Kon |first1=Daniel |date=1983 |title=Los chicos de la guerra = The boys of the war |publisher=New English Library |isbn=978-0-450-05611-6 }} (English translation)\n* {{cite journal |last1=McClure |first1=Jason |date=November 2004 |title=The Falklands War: Causes and Lessons |url=http://www.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?AD=ADA524486 |journal=Strategic Insights |volume=3 |issue=11 }}\n* {{cite book |last1=McManners |first1=Hugh |author-link1=Hugh McManners |date=2007 |title=Forgotten Voices of the Falklands |publisher=[[Random House|Ebury]] |isbn=978-0-09-190880-5 |title-link=Forgotten Voices of the Falklands }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Middlebrook |first1=Martin |author-link1=Martin Middlebrook |date=1985 |title=Operation Corporate: The story of the Falklands War, 1982 |publisher=Viking |isbn=978-0-670-80223-4}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Middlebrook |first1=Martin |author-link1=Martin Middlebrook |date=1989 |title=The fight for the \"Malvinas\": The Argentine Forces in the Falklands War |publisher=Viking |isbn=978-0-670-82106-8}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Norton-Taylor |first1=Richard |author-link1=Richard Norton-Taylor |date=1985 |title=The Ponting affair |publisher=Cecil Woolf |isbn=978-0-900821-73-8 }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Ponting |first1=Clive |author-link1=Clive Ponting |date=1985 |title=The right to know: The inside story of the Belgrano affair |publisher=Sphere |isbn=978-0-7221-6944-5 }}\n* Prince, Stephen. \"British command and control in the Falklands Campaign.\" ''Defense & Security Analysis'' 18.4 (2002): 333-349.\n* {{cite book |last1=Tinker |first1=David |author-link1=David Tinker |date=1982 |title=A message from the Falklands: The life and gallant death of David Tinker: From his letters and poems |publisher=Penguin |isbn=978-0-14-006778-1 }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Thornton |first1=Richard C. |date=1998 |title=The Falklands sting: Reagan, Thatcher, and Argentina's bomb |publisher=Brassey's |isbn=978-1-57488-155-4 |url=https://archive.org/details/falklandsstingre00thor }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Underwood |first1=Geoffrey |date=1983 |title=Our Falklands war: The men of the task force tell their story |publisher=Maritime Books |isbn=978-0-907771-08-1 }}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Ward |first1=Nigel |author-link1=Nigel Ward |date=2000 |title=Sea harrier over the Falklands |publisher=Cassell |isbn=978-0-304-35542-6 }}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Woodward |first1=Sandy |author-link1=Sandy Woodward |last2=Robinson |first2=Patrick |author-link2=Patrick Robinson (author) |date=1997 |title=One hundred days: The memoirs of the Falklands battle group commander |publisher=Naval Institute Press |isbn=978-1-55750-652-8 }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n=== Historiography ===\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Caviedes | first1 = C\u00e9sar N | year = 1994 | title = Conflict over the Falkland Islands: A never-ending story? | journal = Latin American Research Review | volume = 29 | issue = 2| pages = 172\u201387 }}\n* Little, Walter. \"The Falklands Affair: A Review of the Literature,\" ''Political Studies,'' (June 1984) 32#2 pp 296\u2013310\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Tulchin | first1 = Joseph S | year = 1987 | title = The Malvinas War of 1982: An Inevitable Conflict That Never Should Have Occurred | journal = Latin American Research Review | volume = 22 | issue = 3| pages = 123\u2013141 }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Prone to spam|date=June 2019}}\n{{Z148}}<!--     {{No more links}}\n\n       Please be cautious adding more external links.\n\nWikipedia is not a collection of links and should not be used for advertising.\n\n     Excessive or inappropriate links will be removed.\n\n See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.\n\nIf there are already suitable links, propose additions or replacements on\nthe article's talk page.\n\n-->\n* [http://www.fundacionmalvinas.org Argentine website with opinion pieces and photos of the war]\n* [http://dag.un.org/handle/11176/89711 Interview with the then British UN ambassador about initial post invasion peace efforts]\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/FalklandIslandsHistoryRollofHonour.cfm |title=Falkland Islands History Roll of Honour |website=[[Royal Air Force]] |access-date=8 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402162858/http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/FalklandIslandsHistoryRollofHonour.cfm |archive-date=2 April 2015 |url-status=dead  }}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.falklandswar.org.uk |title=The Falkland Islands Conflict 1982 |website=falklandswar.org.uk}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Schumann |first1=Peter B. |url=http://www.dradio.de/dlf/sendungen/einewelt/485782/ |title=Argentiniens unbew\u00e4ltigte Vergangenheit |trans-title=Argentina's unresolved past |website=[[Deutschlandfunk]] |language=German }}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.sama82.org.uk |title=The South Atlantic Medal Association 1982 |website=sama82.org.uk}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.naval-history.net/NAVAL1982FALKLANDS.htm |title=Battle atlas of the Falklands war 1982 by land, sea and air |website=naval-history.net }}\n* {{London Gazette|issue=49134|pages=12831\u201312861 |supp=y|date=8 October 1982|ref=none}} Victoria Cross and other decorations\n* {{London Gazette|issue=48999 |supp=y|pages=7421\u20137422|date=3 June 1982|ref=none}} Decorations specifically for the defence of South Georgia\n* {{cite journal|year=2002 |title=ITB Bater\u00eda Costera Exocet en Malvinas: Entrevista con el CL (R) Ing. Julio P\u00e9rez |trans-title=ITB Exocet battery: Interview with Julio P\u00e9rez |url=http://www.fuerzasnavales.com/itb.html |journal=Fuerzas Navales Magazine |issue=14 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080302010742/http://www.fuerzasnavales.com/itb.html |archive-date=2 March 2008 }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051013064840/http://www.cecim.org.ar/ ex-7th Argentine Infantry Regiment veterans] {{in lang|es}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://radiotapes.com/specialpostings.html#Falklands |title=Coverage of the Falklands war |website=RadioTapes.com}}\n* {{cite wikisource |display-authors=2 |last1=Rey |first1=Carlos Alberto |last2=Rattenbach |first2=Benjam\u00edn |last3=Vago |first3=Alberto Pablo |last4=Boffi |first4=Jorge Alberto |last5=De Bustamante |first5=Tomas Sanchez |last6=Cabrera |first6=Francisco |title=Report Rattenbach: Report of the commission for analysis and evaluation of responsibility in the conflict `South Atlantic` |wslink=Informe Rattenbach |wslanguage=es}}\n* {{cite report |url=http://www.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?AD=ADA566546 |title=Operation Corporate: Operational Art and Implications for the Joint Operational Access Concept |author=Paul A Olsen |work=School of Advanced Military Studies |publisher=DTIC |id=ADA566546 |date=17 May 2012}}\n* {{cite report |url=http://handle.dtic.mil/100.2/ADA133333 |title=Lessons of the Falklands |work=Department of the Navy |publisher=DTIC |id=ADA133333 |date=February 1983}}\n\n{{Falklands War|style=wide}}\n{{navboxes|list=\n{{Argentina topics}}\n{{Falkland Islands topics}}\n{{Margaret Thatcher}}\n{{British colonial campaigns}}}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Falklands War| ]]\n[[Category:1982 in Argentina]]\n[[Category:1982 in the Falkland Islands]]\n[[Category:1982 in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:20th-century military history of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Argentina\u2013United Kingdom military relations]]\n[[Category:Blockades]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1982]]\n[[Category:Invasions by Argentina]]\n[[Category:Invasions of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Argentina]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Coreydragon", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSinking of ARA General Belgrano", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Falklands_War"}
{"title_page": "Bhanupratappur", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Bhanupratappur\n| other_name              = \n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         =  Semiurban\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India Chhattisgarh#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Chhattisgarh, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|20.310079|N|81.071930|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Chhattisgarh]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Kanker district|Kanker]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = Notified Area Council\n| governing_body          = Nagar Panchayat Bhanupratappur\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = 8,856\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]], [[Chhattisgarhi language|Chhattisgarhi]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 494 669\n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| area_code               = +91 7850\n| registration_plate      = CG 19\n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Bhanupratappur''' is a town and a [[Nagar Panchayat | Notified Area Council]] in [[Kanker district]] in the [[Indian state]] of [[Chhattisgarh]].<ref name=C1>{{Cite web |url=http://www.census2011.co.in/data/town/802055-bhanupratappur-chhattisgarh.html |title=Bhanupratappur City Population Census 2011 - Chhattisgarh |website=www.census2011.co.in |access-date=27 November 2018}}</ref> It is also the headquarters of its namesake development [[Block (district subdivision)|block]],  [[tehsil]], and constituency of the [[Chhattisgarh Legislative Assembly]]. The town derives its name from King Bhanupratap Dev, the last ruler of erstwhile [[Kanker district#Kanker Princely State|Kanker]] princely state.<ref>[http://rulers.org/indstat2.html History of Kanker]</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the [[2017-18 Census report of district government]], Bhanupratappur has a population of 8,856. Males constitute 49.7% (4401) of the population whereas females constitute 50.3% (4455). The sex ratio is 1012 females per 1000 males, higher than the national average of 940 per 1000. Children below 6 years of age constitute 10.87% of the population with child sex ratio at 941 males per 1000 females.\n\nThe effective literacy rate is 90.47%; male literacy rate being 95.48% and female literacy rate being 84.97%, significantly higher than the national average of 73%.\n\nHindus comprise the majority with 87.84% of the population. Muslims comprise 4.3%, Sikhs 2.13%, Christians 1.42%, Jains 1.02%, and Buddhists 0.79%. Of the population, 2.50% did not identify themselves with any religion, whereas 0.01% did not want to reveal their religion.<ref name=C1 />\n\n==Transportation==\n\n===Railways===\n[[Bhanupratappur railway station|Bhanupratappur]] was connected to the [[Indian Railways|Indian Railway network]] on 14 April 2018 as part of the [[Dalli-Rajhara-Jagdalpur line]] of [[South East Central Railway zone]]. The DEMU train to [[Raipur]] was flagged off by the Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]]. The railway line has established direct rail connectivity between Bhanupratappur and the state capital, Raipur(142&nbsp;km away), as well as the industrial town of [[Bhilai]](120&nbsp;km away).<ref>https://indiarailinfo.com/train/-train-keoti-raipur-demu-78816/8127/12395/185</ref>\n\n===Air transport===\nThe nearest airport is [[Swami Vivekananda Airport]] in Raipur, around 150&nbsp;km away by road.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Kanker district]]\n[[Category:Kanker district]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Bhanupratappur\n| other_name              = \n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         =  Semiurban\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India Chhattisgarh#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Chhattisgarh, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|20.310079|N|81.071930|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Chhattisgarh]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Kanker district|Kanker]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = Notified Area Council\n| governing_body          = Nagar Panchayat Bhanupratappur\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = 8,856\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]], [[Chhattisgarhi language|Chhattisgarhi]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 494 669\n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| area_code               = +91 7850\n| registration_plate      = CG 19\n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Bhanupratappur''' is a town and a [[Nagar Panchayat | Notified Area Council]] in [[Kanker district]] in the [[Indian state]] of [[Chhattisgarh]].<ref name=C1>{{Cite web |url=http://www.census2011.co.in/data/town/802055-bhanupratappur-chhattisgarh.html |title=Bhanupratappur City Population Census 2011 - Chhattisgarh |website=www.census2011.co.in |access-date=27 November 2018}}</ref> It is also the headquarters of its namesake development [[Block (district subdivision)|block]],  [[tehsil]], and constituency of the [[Chhattisgarh Legislative Assembly]]. The town derives its name from King Bhanupratap Dev, the last ruler of erstwhile [[Kanker district#Kanker Princely State|Kanker]] princely state.<ref>[http://rulers.org/indstat2.html History of Kanker]</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the [[2017-18 Census report of district government]], Bhanupratappur has a population of 8,856. Males constitute 49.7% (4401) of the population whereas females constitute 50.3% (4455). The sex ratio is 1012 females per 1000 males, higher than the national average of 940 per 1000. Children below 6 years of age constitute 10.87% of the population with child sex ratio at 941 males per 1000 females.\n\nThe effective literacy rate is 90.47%; male literacy rate being 95.48% and female literacy rate being 84.97%, significantly higher than the national average of 73%.\n\nHindus comprise the majority with 87.84% of the population. Muslims comprise 4.3%, Sikhs 2.13%, Christians 1.42%, Jains 1.02%, and Buddhists 0.79%. Of the population, 2.50% did not identify themselves with any religion, whereas 0.01% did not want to reveal their religion.<ref name=C1 />\n\n==Transportation==\n\n===Railways===\nBhanupratappur was connected to the [[Indian Railways|Indian Railway network]] on 14 April 2018 as part of the [[Dalli-Rajhara-Jagdalpur line]] of [[South East Central Railway zone]]. The DEMU train to [[Raipur]] was flagged off by the Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]]. The railway line has established direct rail connectivity between Bhanupratappur and the state capital, Raipur(142&nbsp;km away), as well as the industrial town of [[Bhilai]](120&nbsp;km away).<ref>https://indiarailinfo.com/train/-train-keoti-raipur-demu-78816/8127/12395/185</ref> \n\n===Air transport===\nThe nearest airport is [[Swami Vivekananda Airport]] in Raipur, around 150&nbsp;km away by road.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Kanker district]]\n[[Category:Kanker district]]\n", "name_user": "KumarHitesh24", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRailways", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhanupratappur"}
{"title_page": "Phenylthiocarbamide", "text_new": "{{Chembox\n| Verifiedfields = changed\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 451885355\n| ImageFileL1 = Phenylthiocarbamide structure.svg\n| ImageFileR1 = Phenylthiourea-from-xtal-3D-balls.png\n| PIN = Phenylthiourea <!-- The locant is omitted in monosubstituted symmetrical parent hydrides or parent compounds where there is only one kind of substitutable hydrogen. -->\n| OtherNames = ''N''-Phenylthiourea<br />1-Phenylthiourea <!-- Preferred IUPAC names use the letter locants N, and N'. Numerical locants are no longer used for thiourea in the IUPAC preferred name. -->\n|Section1={{Chembox Identifiers\n| CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|CAS}}\n| CASNo = 103-85-5\n| PubChem = 676454\n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|changed|EBI}}\n| ChEBI = 46261\n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|changed|FDA}}\n| UNII = \n| SMILES = C1=CC=C(C=C1)NC(=S)N\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|changed|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 589165\n| InChI = 1/C7H8N2S/c8-7(10)9-6-4-2-1-3-5-6/h1-5H,(H3,8,9,10)\n| InChIKey = FULZLIGZKMKICU-UHFFFAOYAW\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|changed|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C7H8N2S/c8-7(10)9-6-4-2-1-3-5-6/h1-5H,(H3,8,9,10)\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|changed|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = FULZLIGZKMKICU-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n\n| MeSHName = Phenylthiourea\n }}\n|Section2={{Chembox Properties\n| C=7 | H=8 | N=2 | S=1\n| Appearance = White to slightly yellow powder\n| Density = 1.294 g/cm<sup>3</sup>\n| MeltingPtC = 145 to 150\n| BoilingPt =\n| Solubility = Soluble in boiling water\n }}\n|Section3={{Chembox Hazards\n| MainHazards = \n| NFPA-H = 4\n| NFPA-F = 1\n| NFPA-R = 0\n| NFPA-S =\n| EUClass = {{Hazchem T+}}\n| LD50 = 3 mg/kg (oral, rat)\n }}\n}}\n\n'''Phenylthiocarbamide''' ('''PTC'''), also known as '''phenylthiourea''' ('''PTU'''), is an [[organosulfur compound|organosulfur]] [[thiourea]] containing a [[phenyl]] ring.\n\nIt has the unusual property that it either [[taste]]s very bitter or is virtually tasteless, depending on the [[genetics|genetic]] makeup of the taster. The ability to taste PTC is often treated as a [[Dominant gene|dominant]] genetic trait, although inheritance and expression of this trait are somewhat more complex.<ref name=\"Guo & Reed\">{{cite journal|last1=Guo|title=The genetics of phenylthiocarbamide perception|journal=Annals of Human Biology|date=2001|volume=28|issue=2|pages=111\u2013142|pmc=3349222|doi= 10.1080/03014460151056310 |last2=Reed|first2=D. R.|pmid=11293722}}</ref><ref name=\"Myths of Human Genetics\">{{cite web|last1=McDonald|first1=John H.|title=PTC tasting: The Myth|url=http://udel.edu/~mcdonald/mythptc.html|website=Myths of Human Genetics|accessdate=11 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nPTC also inhibits [[melanogenesis]] and is used to grow transparent fish.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Marine Biotechnology |title= Generating Transparent Zebrafish: A Refined Method to Improve Detection of Gene Expression During Embryonic Development |first1=Johnny |last1=Karlsson |first2= Jonas |last2=von Hofsten |first3=Per-Erik |last3=Olsson |volume=3 |issue=6 |pages=522\u2013527 |year=2001 |pmid=14961324 |doi= 10.1007/s1012601-0053-4}}</ref>\n\nAbout 70% of people can taste PTC, varying from a low of 58% for [[Indigenous Australians]] and [[indigenous peoples of New Guinea]] to 98% for [[indigenous peoples of the Americas]].<ref name=\"SSC\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Kim U, Wooding S, Ricci D, Jorde LB, Drayna D |journal= Human Mutation |title= Worldwide haplotype diversity and coding sequence variation at human bitter taste receptor loci |volume=26 |issue=3 |pages=199\u2013204 |year=2005 |doi=10.1002/humu.20203 |pmid= 16086309}}</ref> One study has found that non-smokers and those not habituated to [[coffee]] or [[tea]] have a statistically higher percentage of tasting PTC than the general population.<ref name=\"Fischer1963\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Fischer R, Griffin F, Kaplan AR |title=Taste thresholds, cigarette smoking, and food dislikes |journal=Medicina Experimentalis. International Journal of Experimental Medicine |volume=9 |issue= 3|pages=151\u201367 |year=1963 |pmid=14083335 |doi=10.1159/000135346}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Kaplan AR, Glanville EV, Fischer R |title=Taste thresholds for bitterness and cigarette smoking |journal=Nature |volume=202 |issue= 4939|pages=1366 |year=1964 |pmid=14210998|doi=10.1038/2021366a0 |bibcode=1964Natur.202.1366K }}</ref> PTC does not occur in food, but related chemicals do, and food choice is related to a person's ability to taste PTC.<ref name=\"Fischer1963\"/><ref>{{cite journal|author=Forrai G, B\u00e1nk\u00f6vi G|year=1984|title=Taste perception for phenylthiourea and food choice\u2014a Hungarian twin study|journal=Acta Physiol Hung |volume=64 |issue=1 |pages=33\u201340|pmid=6541419|last2=B\u00e1nk\u00f6vi}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe genetic taste phenomenon of PTC was discovered in 1931 when [[DuPont]] chemist Arthur Fox accidentally released a cloud of fine crystalline PTC.  A nearby colleague complained about the bitter taste, while Fox, who was closer and should have received a strong dose, tasted nothing.  Fox then continued to test the taste buds of assorted family and friends, setting the groundwork for future genetic studies.  The genetic [[penetrance]] was so strong that it was used in [[DNA paternity testing|paternity tests]] before the advent of [[DNA]] matching.<ref>{{cite web|author=Lee Phillips M|title=Scientists Find Bitter Taste Gene|url=http://faculty.washington.edu/chudler/bitter.html|date=15 July 2003|accessdate=5 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe PTC taste test has been widely used in school and college practical teaching as an example of [[Mendelian]] polymorphism in human populations. Based on a taste test, usually of a piece of paper soaked in PTC (or the less toxic [[propylthiouracil]] (PROP)), students are divided into taster and non-taster groups. By assuming that PTC tasting is determined by a [[Dominance (genetics)|dominant]] [[allele]] at a single [[autosomal]] gene, and that the class is an unbiased sample from a population in [[Hardy\u2013Weinberg equilibrium]], students then estimate allele and genotype frequencies within the larger population. While this interpretation is broadly consistent with numerous studies of this trait, it is worth noting that other genes, sex, age and environmental factors influence sensitivity to PTC.<ref name=\"Guo & Reed\" /><ref name=\"Myths of Human Genetics\" /> Also, there are several alleles segregating at the major gene determining the taste of PTC, particularly in African populations, and the common \"taster\" allele is incompletely dominant ([[homozygote]]s for this allele are more sensitive to PTC than are [[heterozygote]]s).<ref name=\"Myths of Human Genetics\" /><ref name=\"Campbell et al. 2012\" /> Additionally, PTC is toxic and sensitivity to the substitute, PROP, does not show a strong association with the gene controlling ability to taste PTC.<ref name=\"Myths of Human Genetics\" />\n\n== Role in taste ==\nThere is a large body of evidence linking the ability to taste [[Thiourea|thiourea compounds]] and dietary habits.  Much of this work has focused on [[Propylthiouracil|6-propyl-2-thiouracil]] (PROP), a compound related to PTC that has lower toxicity.<ref name=\"SSC\"/> A [[supertaster]] has more of an ability to taste PTC.  On the other hand, heavy cigarette smokers are more likely to have high PTC and PROP thresholds (i.e. are relatively insensitive).\n\nIn 1976, an inverse relationship between taster status for PTC and for a bitter component of the fruit of the tree ''[[Antidesma bunius]]'' was discovered.<ref name = \"Henkin and Gillis\">{{cite journal |author1=Henkin, R.I.  |author2=W.T. Gillis  |lastauthoramp=yes | year = 1977 | title = Divergent taste responsiveness to fruit of the tree ''Antidesma bunius'' | journal = Nature | volume = 265 | pages = 536\u2013537 | doi = 10.1038/265536a0 | issue = 5594 | pmid = 834304| bibcode = 1977Natur.265..536H }}</ref> Research on the implications still continues.\n\nAbility to taste PTC may be correlated with a dislike of plants in the genus ''[[Brassica]]'', presumably due to chemical similarities. However, studies in Africa show a poor correlation between PTC tasting and dietary differences.<ref name=\"Campbell et al. 2012\" />\n\n== Genetics ==\n{{main|PTC tasting}}\nMuch of the variation in tasting of PTC is associated with polymorphism at the [[TAS2R38]] taste receptor gene.<ref name=\"Drayna 2005\">{{cite journal|last1=Drayna|first1=Dennis|title=Human Taste Genetics|journal=Annual Review of Genomics and Human Genetics|date=2005|volume=6|pages=217\u2013235|pmid=16124860|doi=10.1146/annurev.genom.6.080604.162340}}</ref> In humans, there are three SNPs ([[single nucleotide polymorphisms]]) along the [[gene]] that may render its proteins unresponsive.<ref name=\"Kim 2003\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Kim UK, Jorgenson E, Coon H, Leppert M, Risch N, Drayna D | title=Positional cloning of the human quantitative trait locus underlying taste sensitivity to phenylthiocarbamide  |journal=Science  |year=2003 | volume=299 | issue=5610 | pages=1221\u20131225 | pmid=12595690 | doi=10.1126/science.1080190 |bibcode=2003Sci...299.1221K}}</ref> There is conflicting evidence as to whether the inheritance of this trait is [[dominance (genetics)|dominant]] or [[incomplete dominance|incompletely dominant]].<ref name=\"Myths of Human Genetics\" /> Any person with a single functional copy of this gene can make the protein and is sensitive to PTC.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} Some studies have shown that [[homozygous]] tasters experience a more intense bitterness than people that are [[heterozygous]]; other studies have indicated that another gene may determine taste sensitivity.<ref name=\"Guo & Reed\" />\n\nThe frequency of PTC taster and non-taster [[allele]]s vary in different human populations.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fareed |first1=M. |last2=Shah |first2=A. |last3=Hussain |first3=R. |last4=Afzal |first4=M. |year=2012 |title=Genetic study of phenylthiocarbamide (PTC) taste perception among six human populations of Jammu and Kashmir (India) |journal=Egypt J Med Hum Genet |volume=13 |pages=161\u2013166 |doi=10.1016/j.ejmhg.2012.01.003 |issue=2|doi-access=free }}</ref> The widespread occurrence of non-taster alleles at intermediate frequencies, much more common than recessive alleles conferring genetic disease, across many isolated populations, suggests that this polymorphism may have been maintained through balancing selection.<ref name=\"Campbell et al. 2012\">{{cite journal|last1=Campbell|title=Evolution of Functionally Diverse Alleles Associated with PTC Bitter Taste Sensitivity in Africa|journal=Molecular Biology and Evolution|date=2012|volume=29|issue=4|pages=1141\u20131153|pmc=3341826|displayauthors=etal |pmid=22130969|doi=10.1093/molbev/msr293}}</ref>\n\n[[Common chimpanzee|Chimpanzees]] and [[orangutans]] also vary in their ability to taste PTC, with the proportions of tasters and non-tasters similar to that in humans.<ref name=\"Fisher, Ford & Huxley\">{{cite journal|last1=Fisher, Ford & Huxley|first1=R. A.|last2=Ford|first2=E. B.|last3=Huxley|first3=Julian|title=Taste-testing the Anthropoid Apes|journal=Nature|date=28 October 1939|volume=144|issue=750|pages=750|doi=10.1038/144750a0|bibcode=1939Natur.144..750F|hdl=2440/15129|url=https://digital.library.adelaide.edu.au/dspace/bitstream/2440/15129/1/170.pdf}}</ref> The ability to taste PTC is an ancestral trait of hominids that has been independently lost in humans and chimpanzees, through distinct mutations at [[TAS2R38]].<ref name=\"Wooding et al. 2006\">{{cite journal |last1=Wooding |first1=Stephen |title=Independent evolution of bitter-taste sensitivity in humans and chimpanzees |journal=Nature |date=2006 |volume=440 |issue=7086 |pages=930\u2013934 |doi=10.1038/nature04655 |pmid=16612383 |displayauthors=1 |last2=Grassi |first2=Christina |last3=Howard |first3=Michael T. |last4=Stone |first4=Anne C. |last5=Vazquez |first5=Maribel |last6=Dunn |first6=Diane M. |last7=Meyerhof |first7=Wolfgang |last8=Weiss |first8=Robert B. |last9=Bamshad |first9=Michael J. |bibcode=2006Natur.440..930W}}</ref>\n\n===Non-taster phenotype distribution (%) in selected populations===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ align=\"bottom\"|Results of multiple PTC taste tests in different regions done with the discrimination method developed by Harris and Kalmus in 1949, published in [[Annals of Eugenics]].<ref name=\"Harris (1949)\">{{cite journal | last1 = Harris | first1 = H. | last2 = Kalmus | first2 = H. | year = 1949 | title = The measurement of taste sensitivity to phenylthiourea (PTC) | url = | journal = Ann. Eugen | volume = 15 | issue = | pages = 24\u201331 | pmid = 15403125 }}</ref>\n!Location!!# of Participants!!Non-taster %!!References\n|-\n| [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n| 7,362\n| 32.02\n| Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 et al. (1982)<ref name=\"Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 R (1982)\">{{cite journal | last1 = Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 | first1 = R. | last2 = Novosel | first2 = V. | last3 = Bukvi\u0107 | first3 = S. | last4 = Vrbi\u0107 | first4 = N. | year = 1982 | title = Distribucija praga nadra\u017eaja za ukus feniltiokarbamida (PTC) u tri uzorka stanovni\u0161tva Jugoslavije | url = | journal = God. Biol. inst. Univ. u Sarajevu | volume = 35 | issue = | pages = 72\u201380 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Croatia]]\n| 200\n| 27.5\n| Gr\u00fcnwald, Pfeifer (1962)\n|-\n| [[Czech Republic]]\n| 785\n| 32.7\n| Kubi\u010dkova, Dvo\u0159akov\u00e1 (1968)\n|-\n| [[Denmark]]\n| 251\n| 32.7\n| Harrison et al. (1977)<ref name=\"Harrison (1977)\">Harrison et al. (1977): Human biology \u2013 An introduction to human evolution, variation, growth and ecology. Oxford University Press, Oxford, {{ISBN|978-0-19-857164-3}}; {{ISBN|978-0-19-857165-0}}.</ref>\n|-\n| [[England]]\n| 441\n| 31.5\n| Harrison et al. (1977)<ref name=\"Harrison (1977)\"/>\n|-\n| [[Hungary]]\n| 436\n| 32.2\n| Forai, Bankovi (1967) \n|-\n| [[Italy]]\n| 1,031\n| 29.19\n|Floris et al. (1976)\n|-\n| [[Montenegro]]\n| 256\n| 28.20\n| Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 et al. (1982)<ref name=\"Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 R (1982)\"/>\n|-\n| [[U\u017eice]], [[Serbia]]\n| 1,129\n| 16.65\n| Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 et al. (1982)<ref name=\"Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 R (1982)\"/>\n|-\n| [[Voivodina]], [[Serbia]]\n| 600\n| 26.3\n| Bo\u017ei\u0107, Gavrilovi\u0107 (1973)\n|-\n| [[Russia]]\n| 486\n| 36.6\n| Boyd (1950)\n|-\n| [[Slovenia]]\n| 126\n| 37.3\n| Brodar (1970)\n|-\n| [[Spain]]\n| 203\n| 25.6\n| Harrison et al. (1977)<ref name=\"Harrison (1977)\"/>\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[TAS2R38]]\n* [[List of Mendelian traits in humans]]\n* ''[[Antidesma bunius]]''\n* [[Propylthiouracil]]\n* [[Cilantro]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090324090838/https://www.nidcd.nih.gov/research/scientists/draynad.asp Dennis Drayna's home page.]  Drayna has done extensive studies of PTC in various populations\n* [http://www.iit.edu/~smile/bi9113.html Population Study and Applications Using PTC Paper]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060215070738/http://genetics-education-partnership.mbt.washington.edu/cool/tools/ptcpaper.html Classroom activity description using PTC paper]\n* {{OMIM|171200}} Thiourea tasting\n\n{{Cruciferous Biochemistry}}\n\n[[Category:Phenyl compounds]]\n[[Category:Human genetics]]\n[[Category:Thioureas]]\n[[Category:Bitter compounds]]\n", "text_old": "{{Chembox\n| Verifiedfields = changed\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 451885355\n| ImageFileL1 = Phenylthiocarbamide structure.svg\n| ImageFileR1 = Phenylthiourea-from-xtal-3D-balls.png\n| PIN = Phenylthiourea <!-- The locant is omitted in monosubstituted symmetrical parent hydrides or parent compounds where there is only one kind of substitutable hydrogen. -->\n| OtherNames = ''N''-Phenylthiourea<br />1-Phenylthiourea <!-- Preferred IUPAC names use the letter locants N, and N'. Numerical locants are no longer used for thiourea in the IUPAC preferred name. -->\n|Section1={{Chembox Identifiers\n| CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|CAS}}\n| CASNo = 103-85-5\n| PubChem = 676454\n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|changed|EBI}}\n| ChEBI = 46261\n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|changed|FDA}}\n| UNII = \n| SMILES = C1=CC=C(C=C1)NC(=S)N\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|changed|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 589165\n| InChI = 1/C7H8N2S/c8-7(10)9-6-4-2-1-3-5-6/h1-5H,(H3,8,9,10)\n| InChIKey = FULZLIGZKMKICU-UHFFFAOYAW\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|changed|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C7H8N2S/c8-7(10)9-6-4-2-1-3-5-6/h1-5H,(H3,8,9,10)\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|changed|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = FULZLIGZKMKICU-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n\n| MeSHName = Phenylthiourea\n }}\n|Section2={{Chembox Properties\n| C=7 | H=8 | N=2 | S=1\n| Appearance = White to slightly yellow powder\n| Density = 1.294 g/cm<sup>3</sup>\n| MeltingPtC = 145 to 150\n| BoilingPt =\n| Solubility = Soluble in boiling water\n }}\n|Section3={{Chembox Hazards\n| MainHazards = \n| NFPA-H = 4\n| NFPA-F = 1\n| NFPA-R = 0\n| NFPA-S =\n| EUClass = {{Hazchem T+}}\n| LD50 = 3 mg/kg (oral, rat)\n }}\n}}\n\n'''Phenylthiocarbamide''' ('''PTC'''), also known as '''phenylthiourea''' ('''PTU'''), is an [[organosulfur compound|organosulfur]] [[thiourea]] containing a [[phenyl]] ring.\n\nIt has the unusual property that it either [[taste]]s very bitter or is virtually tasteless, depending on the [[genetics|genetic]] makeup of the taster. The ability to taste PTC is often treated as a [[Dominant gene|dominant]] genetic trait, although inheritance and expression of this trait are somewhat more complex.<ref name=\"Guo & Reed\">{{cite journal|last1=Guo|title=The genetics of phenylthiocarbamide perception|journal=Annals of Human Biology|date=2001|volume=28|issue=2|pages=111\u2013142|pmc=3349222|doi= 10.1080/03014460151056310 |last2=Reed|first2=D. R.|pmid=11293722}}</ref><ref name=\"Myths of Human Genetics\">{{cite web|last1=McDonald|first1=John H.|title=PTC tasting: The Myth|url=http://udel.edu/~mcdonald/mythptc.html|website=Myths of Human Genetics|accessdate=11 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nPTC also inhibits [[melanogenesis]] and is used to grow transparent fish.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Marine Biotechnology |title= Generating Transparent Zebrafish: A Refined Method to Improve Detection of Gene Expression During Embryonic Development |first1=Johnny |last1=Karlsson |first2= Jonas |last2=von Hofsten |first3=Per-Erik |last3=Olsson |volume=3 |issue=6 |pages=522\u2013527 |year=2001 |pmid=14961324 |doi= 10.1007/s1012601-0053-4}}</ref>\n\nAbout 70% of people can taste PTC, varying from a low of 58% for [[Indigenous Australians]] and [[indigenous peoples of New Guinea]] to 98% for [[indigenous peoples of the Americas]].<ref name=\"SSC\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Kim U, Wooding S, Ricci D, Jorde LB, Drayna D |journal= Human Mutation |title= Worldwide haplotype diversity and coding sequence variation at human bitter taste receptor loci |volume=26 |issue=3 |pages=199\u2013204 |year=2005 |doi=10.1002/humu.20203 |pmid= 16086309}}</ref> One study has found that non-smokers and those not habituated to [[coffee]] or [[tea]] have a statistically higher percentage of tasting PTC than the general population.<ref name=\"Fischer1963\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Fischer R, Griffin F, Kaplan AR |title=Taste thresholds, cigarette smoking, and food dislikes |journal=Medicina Experimentalis. International Journal of Experimental Medicine |volume=9 |issue= 3|pages=151\u201367 |year=1963 |pmid=14083335 |doi=10.1159/000135346}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Kaplan AR, Glanville EV, Fischer R |title=Taste thresholds for bitterness and cigarette smoking |journal=Nature |volume=202 |issue= 4939|pages=1366 |year=1964 |pmid=14210998|doi=10.1038/2021366a0 |bibcode=1964Natur.202.1366K }}</ref> PTC does not occur in food, but related chemicals do, and food choice is related to a person's ability to taste PTC.<ref name=\"Fischer1963\"/><ref>{{cite journal|author=Forrai G, B\u00e1nk\u00f6vi G|year=1984|title=Taste perception for phenylthiourea and food choice\u2014a Hungarian twin study|journal=Acta Physiol Hung |volume=64 |issue=1 |pages=33\u201340|pmid=6541419|last2=B\u00e1nk\u00f6vi}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe genetic taste phenomenon of PTC was discovered in 1931 when [[DuPont]] chemist Arthur Fox accidentally released a cloud of fine crystalline PTC.  A nearby colleague complained about the bitter taste, while Fox, who was closer and should have received a strong dose, tasted nothing.  Fox then continued to test the taste buds of assorted family and friends, setting the groundwork for future genetic studies.  The genetic [[penetrance]] was so strong that it was used in [[DNA paternity testing|paternity tests]] before the advent of [[DNA]] matching.<ref>{{cite web|author=Lee Phillips M|title=Scientists Find Bitter Taste Gene|url=http://faculty.washington.edu/chudler/bitter.html|date=15 July 2003|accessdate=5 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe PTC taste test has been widely used in school and college practical teaching as an example of [[Mendelian]] polymorphism in human populations. Based on a taste test, usually of a piece of paper soaked in PTC (or the less toxic [[propylthiouracil]] (PROP)), students are divided into taster and non-taster groups. By assuming that PTC tasting is determined by a [[Dominance (genetics)|dominant]] [[allele]] at a single [[autosomal]] gene, and that the class is an unbiased sample from a population in [[Hardy\u2013Weinberg equilibrium]], students then estimate allele and genotype frequencies within the larger population. While this interpretation is broadly consistent with numerous studies of this trait, it is worth noting that other genes, sex, age and environmental factors influence sensitivity to PTC.<ref name=\"Guo & Reed\" /><ref name=\"Myths of Human Genetics\" /> Also, there are several alleles segregating at the major gene determining the taste of PTC, particularly in African populations, and the common \"taster\" allele is incompletely dominant ([[homozygote]]s for this allele are more sensitive to PTC than are [[heterozygote]]s).<ref name=\"Myths of Human Genetics\" /><ref name=\"Campbell et al. 2012\" /> Additionally, PTC is toxic and sensitivity to the substitute, PROP, does not show a strong association with the gene controlling ability to taste PTC.<ref name=\"Myths of Human Genetics\" />\n\n== Role in taste ==\nThere is a large body of evidence linking the ability to taste [[Thiourea|thiourea compounds]] and dietary habits.  Much of this work has focused on [[Propylthiouracil|6-propyl-2-thiouracil]] (PROP), a compound related to PTC that has lower toxicity.<ref name=\"SSC\"/> A [[supertaster]] has more of an ability to taste PTC.  On the other hand, heavy cigarette smokers are more likely to have high PTC and PROP thresholds (i.e. are relatively insensitive).\n\nIn 1976, an inverse relationship between taster status for PTC and for a bitter component of the fruit of the tree ''[[Antidesma bunius]]'' was discovered.<ref name = \"Henkin and Gillis\">{{cite journal |author1=Henkin, R.I.  |author2=W.T. Gillis  |lastauthoramp=yes | year = 1977 | title = Divergent taste responsiveness to fruit of the tree ''Antidesma bunius'' | journal = Nature | volume = 265 | pages = 536\u2013537 | doi = 10.1038/265536a0 | issue = 5594 | pmid = 834304| bibcode = 1977Natur.265..536H }}</ref> Research on the implications still continues.\n\nAbility to taste PTC may be correlated with a dislike of plants in the genus ''[[Brassica]]'', presumably due to chemical similarities. However, studies in Africa show a poor correlation between PTC tasting and dietary differences.<ref name=\"Campbell et al. 2012\" />\n\n== Genetics ==\n{{main|PTC tasting}}\nMuch of the variation in tasting of PTC is associated with polymorphism at the [[TAS2R38]] taste receptor gene.<ref name=\"Drayna 2005\">{{cite journal|last1=Drayna|first1=Dennis|title=Human Taste Genetics|journal=Annual Review of Genomics and Human Genetics|date=2005|volume=6|pages=217\u2013235|pmid=16124860|doi=10.1146/annurev.genom.6.080604.162340}}</ref> In humans, there are three SNPs ([[single nucleotide polymorphisms]]) along the [[gene]] that may render its proteins unresponsive.<ref name=\"Kim 2003\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Kim UK, Jorgenson E, Coon H, Leppert M, Risch N, Drayna D | title=Positional cloning of the human quantitative trait locus underlying taste sensitivity to phenylthiocarbamide  |journal=Science  |year=2003 | volume=299 | issue=5610 | pages=1221\u20131225 | pmid=12595690 | doi=10.1126/science.1080190 |bibcode=2003Sci...299.1221K}}</ref> There is conflicting evidence as to whether the inheritance of this trait is [[dominance (genetics)|dominant]] or [[incomplete dominance|incompletely dominant]].<ref name=\"Myths of Human Genetics\" /> Any person with a single functional copy of this gene can make the protein and is sensitive to PTC.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} Some studies have shown that [[homozygous]] tasters experience a more intense bitterness than people that are [[heterozygous]]; other studies have indicated that another gene may determine taste sensitivity.<ref name=\"Guo & Reed\" />\n\nThe frequency of PTC taster and non-taster [[allele]]s vary in different human populations.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fareed |first1=M. |last2=Shah |first2=A. |last3=Hussain |first3=R. |last4=Afzal |first4=M. |year=2012 |title=Genetic study of phenylthiocarbamide (PTC) taste perception among six human populations of Jammu and Kashmir (India) |journal=Egypt J Med Hum Genet |volume=13 |pages=161\u2013166 |doi=10.1016/j.ejmhg.2012.01.003 |issue=2|doi-access=free }}</ref> The widespread occurrence of non-taster alleles at intermediate frequencies, much more common than recessive alleles conferring genetic disease, across many isolated populations, suggests that this polymorphism may have been maintained through balancing selection.<ref name=\"Campbell et al. 2012\">{{cite journal|last1=Campbell|title=Evolution of Functionally Diverse Alleles Associated with PTC Bitter Taste Sensitivity in Africa|journal=Molecular Biology and Evolution|date=2012|volume=29|issue=4|pages=1141\u20131153|pmc=3341826|displayauthors=etal |pmid=22130969|doi=10.1093/molbev/msr293}}</ref>\n\n[[Common chimpanzee|Chimpanzees]] and [[orangutans]] also vary in their ability to taste PTC, with the proportions of tasters and non-tasters similar to that in humans.<ref name=\"Fisher, Ford & Huxley\">{{cite journal|last1=Fisher, Ford & Huxley|first1=R. A.|last2=Ford|first2=E. B.|last3=Huxley|first3=Julian|title=Taste-testing the Anthropoid Apes|journal=Nature|date=28 October 1939|volume=144|issue=750|pages=750|doi=10.1038/144750a0|bibcode=1939Natur.144..750F|hdl=2440/15129|url=https://digital.library.adelaide.edu.au/dspace/bitstream/2440/15129/1/170.pdf}}</ref> The ability to taste PTC is an ancestral trait of hominids that has been independently lost in humans and chimpanzees, through distinct mutations at [[TAS2R38]].<ref name=\"Wooding et al. 2006\">{{cite journal |last1=Wooding |first1=Stephen |title=Independent evolution of bitter-taste sensitivity in humans and chimpanzees |journal=Nature |date=2006 |volume=440 |issue=7086 |pages=930\u2013934 |doi=10.1038/nature04655 |pmid=16612383 |displayauthors=1 |last2=Grassi |first2=Christina |last3=Howard |first3=Michael T. |last4=Stone |first4=Anne C. |last5=Vazquez |first5=Maribel |last6=Dunn |first6=Diane M. |last7=Meyerhof |first7=Wolfgang |last8=Weiss |first8=Robert B. |last9=Bamshad |first9=Michael J. |bibcode=2006Natur.440..930W}}</ref>\n\n===Non-taster phenotype distribution (%) in selected populations===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ align=\"bottom\"|Results of multiple PTC taste tests in different regions done with the discrimination method developed by Harris and Kalmus in 1949, published in [[Annals of Eugenics]].<ref name=\"Harris (1949)\">Harris H., Kalmus  H. (1949): The measurement of taste sensitivity to phenylthiourea (PTC). Ann. Eugen. 15: 24-31, 1949. [PubMed: 15403125.]</ref>\n!Location!!# of Participants!!Non-taster %!!References\n|-\n| [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n| 7,362\n| 32.02\n| Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 et al. (1982)<ref name=\"Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 R (1982)\">Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 R., Novosel, V., Bukvi\u0107, S., Vrbi\u0107, N. (1982): Distribucija praga nadra\u017eaja za ukus feniltiokarbamida (PTC) u tri uzorka stanovni\u0161tva Jugoslavije. God. Biol. inst. Univ. u Sarajevu, 35: 72-80.</ref>\n|-\n| [[Croatia]]\n| 200\n| 27.5\n| Gr\u00fcnwald, Pfeifer (1962)\n|-\n| [[Czech Republic]]\n| 785\n| 32.7\n| Kubi\u010dkova, Dvo\u0159akov\u00e1 (1968)\n|-\n| [[Denmark]]\n| 251\n| 32.7\n| Harrison et al. (1977)<ref name=\"Harrison (1977)\">Harrison et al. (1977): Human biology \u2013 An introduction to human evolution, variation, growth and ecology. Oxford University Press, Oxford, {{ISBN|978-0-19-857164-3}}; {{ISBN|978-0-19-857165-0}}.</ref>\n|-\n| [[England]]\n| 441\n| 31.5\n| Harrison et al. (1977)<ref name=\"Harrison (1977)\"/>\n|-\n| [[Hungary]]\n| 436\n| 32.2\n| Forai, Bankovi (1967) \n|-\n| [[Italy]]\n| 1,031\n| 29.19\n|Floris et al. (1976)\n|-\n| [[Montenegro]]\n| 256\n| 28.20\n| Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 et al. (1982)<ref name=\"Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 R (1982)\"/>\n|-\n| [[U\u017eice]], [[Serbia]]\n| 1,129\n| 16.65\n| Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 et al. (1982)<ref name=\"Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 R (1982)\"/>\n|-\n| [[Voivodina]], [[Serbia]]\n| 600\n| 26.3\n| Bo\u017ei\u0107, Gavrilovi\u0107 (1973)\n|-\n| [[Russia]]\n| 486\n| 36.6\n| Boyd (1950)\n|-\n| [[Slovenia]]\n| 126\n| 37.3\n| Brodar (1970)\n|-\n| [[Spain]]\n| 203\n| 25.6\n| Harrison et al. (1977)<ref name=\"Harrison (1977)\"/>\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[TAS2R38]]\n* [[List of Mendelian traits in humans]]\n* ''[[Antidesma bunius]]''\n* [[Propylthiouracil]]\n* [[Cilantro]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090324090838/https://www.nidcd.nih.gov/research/scientists/draynad.asp Dennis Drayna's home page.]  Drayna has done extensive studies of PTC in various populations\n* [http://www.iit.edu/~smile/bi9113.html Population Study and Applications Using PTC Paper]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060215070738/http://genetics-education-partnership.mbt.washington.edu/cool/tools/ptcpaper.html Classroom activity description using PTC paper]\n* {{OMIM|171200}} Thiourea tasting\n\n{{Cruciferous Biochemistry}}\n\n[[Category:Phenyl compounds]]\n[[Category:Human genetics]]\n[[Category:Thioureas]]\n[[Category:Bitter compounds]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phenylthiocarbamide"}
{"title_page": "Firewind", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Firewind\n| image               = Firewind Live.jpg\n| caption             = Firewind performing live in Shanghai\n| image_size          = 250\n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Thessaloniki, Greece]]\n| genre               = [[Power metal]], [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]]\n| years_active        = 1998, 2002\u2013present\n| label               = [[Century Media Records|Century Media]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Ozzy Osbourne]], [[Dream Evil]], [[Mystic Prophecy]], [[Dragonland]], [[Nightrage]], [[Evil Masquerade]], [[Spiritual Beggars]], [[Helloween]], [[Meridian Dawn]], [[Pagan's Mind]], [[Metalium]], [[Nightfall (band)|Nightfall]], [[Septicflesh]], [[Outloud (Greek band)|Outloud]]\n| website                 = [http://www.firewind.gr/ www.firewind.gr]\n| current_members     = [[Gus G]]<br />[[Petros Christo]]doulidis<br />[[Johan Nunez]]<br />Herbie Langhans\n| past_members        = [[Bob Katsionis]] <br />Henning Basse<br />Brandon Pender<br />[[Stephen Fredrick]]<br />[[Chitral Somapala]]<br />[[Kostas Exarhakis]]<br />[[Matt Scurfield]]<br />Brian Harris<br />Stian Kristoffersen<br />[[Mark Cross (musician)|Mark Cross]]<br />Michael Ehr\u00e9<br />[[Apollo Papathanasio]]\n}}\n\n'''Firewind''' is a Greek [[power metal]] band. Formed in 1998, the group is currently signed to [[Century Media Records]] and was originally a small project created by [[guitarist]] [[Gus G.]] to showcase his [[demo (music)|demo]], ''[[Nocturnal Symphony]]'' in 1998. Firewind later became a full band over three years later when they recorded their debut album, ''[[Between Heaven and Hell (album)|Between Heaven and Hell]]''. To date, the band has released eight studio albums and has been met with international success.\n\n==History==\n===Early history===\nThe band began in 1998 when the young [[Greece|Greek]] [[Gus G.]] decided to record a [[demo (music)|demo]] on a 4-track recorder with some close musician friends in the [[United States]] as Gus \"briefly attended [[Berklee College of Music]] in Boston\".<ref name=guitarhoo>{{cite web|title=Gus G. Interview|url=http://www.guitarhoo.com/interviews/gus-g-124|work=Guitarhoo!|publisher=Guitarhoo.com|accessdate=March 6, 2013|date=January 16, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123071055/http://www.guitarhoo.com/interviews/gus-g-124|archive-date=January 23, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The project was entitled Firewind, and was used as a showcase for Gus' guitar skills in an attempt to earn a professional recording deal.<ref>Metal Archives [http://www.metal-archives.com/more.php?id=2025 Firewind history] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081226230027/http://www.metal-archives.com/more.php?id=2025 |date=2008-12-26 }}</ref>  Gus G. was quoted as saying, \"Firewind, the second [[Electric Sun]] album, that's where I got the band name from.\"[https://soundcloud.com/user-90858124/ryan-91818-gus-g R.Y.A.N. - Season 2, Episode 4: Gus G.]  The demo attracted the attention of Leviathan Records, but activity was put on hold when Gus was hired by [[Nightrage]], [[Dream Evil]], and [[Mystic Prophecy]].\n\n===''Between Heaven and Hell''===\nAfter the release of his other bands' debut albums, Gus' attention returned to the Firewind project. Only he remained from the original formation - Leviathan owner [[David T. Chastain]] brought in [[vocalist]] [[Stephen Fredrick]] and [[drummer]] Brian Harris (both formerly of Kenziner), while Gus enlisted the help of [[bassist]] [[Kostas Exarhakis|Konstantine]]. This line-up recorded the debut album ''[[Between Heaven and Hell (album)|Between Heaven and Hell]]''.\n\n===''Burning Earth''===\nIn 2003, new changes were instituted as drummer Stian Kristoffersen and bassist [[Petros Christo]] joined the band. Harris and Konstantine had been replaced as Gus was looking for a more permanent [[rhythm section]] that was prepared to tour. This lineup recorded ''[[Burning Earth]]'' and went on a tour of [[Japan]] with [[Rob Rock]], but without vocalist Fredrick, who was not prepared to go on the road (despite prior guarantees to the contrary). At their October 2007 show at [[ProgPower USA]], the band briefly reunited with Fredrick for a few songs off their first two albums.\n\n===''Forged by Fire''===\nFredrick's replacement on the Burning the Earth Tour, singer [[Chitral Somapala|Chitral \"Chity\" Somapala]], was given the job full-time. Fellow touring member [[Bob Katsionis]] was also hired permanently to play keyboards. Firewind got a worldwide deal with [[Century Media]] by the end of that year.\n\nA few months after ''[[Forged By Fire]]'' was released, Chitral left due to personal and musical differences with the rest of the band. When his replacement, [[Apollo Papathanasio]] (of [[Time Requiem]]), was found, it was also announced that Kristoffersen would be leaving, to be replaced by [[United Kingdom|British]] drummer [[Mark Cross (musician)|Mark Cross]]. The reason for the split was that Gus wanted to have a set of Greek-based musicians willing to make Firewind their number one priority (probably to end the virtual [[revolving door]] of members) and Stian's main band was the [[Norway|Norwegian]] outfit [[Pagan's Mind]]. Gus also left his roles in Dream Evil, Mystic Prophecy and [[Nightrage]].\n\n===''Allegiance'' and ''The Premonition''===\nBetween 2004 and 2006, the band recorded ''[[Allegiance (Firewind album)|Allegiance]]'', which was released in July 2006. From November to December 2006, they toured the UK supporting [[DragonForce]] with [[All That Remains (band)|All That Remains]]. Firewind accomplished their 2006/2007 world tour in [[Copenhagen]] at the Scandinavian Prog Power festival on November 10. The band went around the globe almost twice being on three continents including [[Asia]], [[Africa]], [[North America]] and Europe and played nearly 100 shows. The band went to [[Sweden]] to record ''[[The Premonition (album)|The Premonition]]'', which was released in 2008.<ref>[http://www.komodorock.com/reviews/cd-reviews/firewind-%11-the-premonition-200802144281/ The Premonition - Review] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215192512/http://www.komodorock.com/reviews/cd-reviews/firewind-%11-the-premonition-200802144281/ |date=2008-02-15 }} Feb 14. 2008</ref>\n\n[[File:Firewind live in Paris.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Firewind performing live in France in 2008.]]\n\nIn November 2008, the band released their first DVD, ''Live Premonition'', containing footage of their entire concert at their home town in Greece on January 12 of that year. The band toured with [[Stratovarius]] in the UK during May 2009. During this tour, they added two new songs to their setlist, \"Losing Faith\" and \"Days of No Trust\". \"Losing Faith\", which contains a line in the chorus \"in the days of no trust\", was eventually to appear on 2009's  ''[[Days of Defiance]]''. In 2010 Firewind appeared in Issue 3 of the [[Eternal Descent]] Comic Book series. The narrative was inspired by lyrics from 'Angels Forgive Me' featured on 'The Premonition'\n\n===''Days of Defiance''===\nAt the end of September 2009, Firewind began work on their sixth studio album, the band confirmed that they have written twelve vocal and two instrumental songs.\n\nOn January 13, 2010, Firewind announced that they were parting ways with drummer [[Mark Cross (musician)|Mark Cross]] (Tower of Babel, God\u00b4s Army), with Michael Ehr\u00e9 (Uli Jon Roth, Metalium, Kee Marcello) playing at the live Mexico shows. Those shows, however, were cancelled. On May 7, the band recorded a cover of [[Judas Priest]]'s \"[[Breaking the Law]]\" for a compilation CD by the magazine ''[[Metal Hammer]]''. On May 26, Firewind announced the name of their new album as ''[[Days of Defiance]]'' and confirmed Michael Ehr\u00e9 as a full-time member although Mark Cross had recorded all drums on the album.\n\nOn August 6, 2010, they confirmed an October release date for their sixth studio album ''Days of Defiance'', and an August release date for the album's first single \"[[World on Fire (Firewind song)|World on Fire]]\". On the weekend of August 20\u201322, Gus G guest appeared on the radio show [[Full Metal Jackie]] where he premi\u00e8red a second song from the album, titled \"Embrace the Sun\".\n\nAlmost a year after the release of ''Days of Defiance'', Firewind did a European headlining tour, with [[Mats Lev\u00e9n]] as a replacement for Apollo who couldn't make the European leg of the tour and a US headlining tour. Gus has said in an interview that Firewind will probably do a South America(this never happened) tour after the US tour and than enter the studio for a new album. Also has Michael Ehr\u00e9 left Firewind and [[Johan Nunez]] of [[Nightrage]] replaced him on the tours and now is a full member of the band.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metalassault.com/Interviews/082911_Firewind.php |title=Firewind: In-depth Interview With Gus G (Audio) |website=Metalassault.com |date=2011-08-29 |accessdate=2011-09-14}}</ref>\n\n===''Few Against Many'' and 10th anniversary===\nJohan Nunez joined the session for the seventh studio album as drummer in Valve Studio in Greece.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_DB1q7M7b2I/ |title=Firewind - Studio Diary Part 1 |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2011-12-06 |accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nFirewind debuted two songs, \"Wall Of Sound\" and \"Losing My Mind\", from their seventh studio album at headlining shows in Greece.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VratJYXZuYs |title=YouTube |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date= |accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref> The band has been confirmed for the Summer Breeze Festival and the Masters Of Rock festival.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firewind.gr/2008/tour.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-01-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208004254/http://www.firewind.gr/2008/tour.html |archivedate=2012-02-08 }}</ref> In early 2012, Firewind and Century Media have announced that Firewind has re-signed with the label and that they will be releasing the new album titled \"[[Few Against Many]]\" May 21 in Europe and May 22 in North America. Also Firewind's second album will be re-released throughout Japan with 2 bonus tracks in February 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=168188|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120910030439/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=168188|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-09-10|title=Firewind Signs New European Deal With Century Media Records |website=Blabbermouth.net}}</ref> The band was confirmed to perform at the [[Download Festival]] in June 2012.\n\nOn September 5, 2012, Firewind released a music video entitled \"Edge of a Dream\" that features [[Apocalyptica]]. It was taken from their ''[[Few Against Many]]'' album released by Century Media Records earlier that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalcallout.com/metal-news/feeling-cheesy-firewind-and-theocracy-have-new-videos-out.html|title=Firewind New Video Out|website=Metalcallout.com|accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref> Later in September 2012, Firewind announced that they would play four anniversary live shows in Greece in December (counting from the release date of Between Heaven and Hell), to celebrate their 10 years of existence. The shows took place on December 15 and 16 in Thessaloniki, and on December 20 and 21 in Athens. The band played different set lists each night in each city. The shows, as the band repeatedly announced were recorded for a live cd release in 2013. Anniversary merchandise was also sold at the venues. On January 15, 2013 Firewind announced that vocalist Apollo Papathanasio had quit the band due to not being able to keep up with the band's touring and promotion schedule.\n\nOn January 15, 2013, the band announced that Kelly Sundown Carpenter ([[Adagio (band)|Adagio]], [[Beyond Twilight]], [[Outworld]], Darkology) would replace Apollo Papathanasio on vocals for their 2013 North American Tour.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firewind.gr/2012/home.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130203033854/http://www.firewind.gr/2012/home.html |archivedate=2013-02-03 }}</ref> During an interview in June 2013 with Metal Shock Finland's Blackdiamond, Gus mentioned Kelly as a fantastic singer and also he stated that they have no plans to record a new studio album yet.<ref>{{cite news|title=GUS G. Talks New FIREWIND Singer, Forthcoming Solo Album, BLACK SABBATH's '13' (Audio)|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=191413|accessdate=19 June 2013|newspaper=Blabbermouth.net|date=17 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Blackdiamond|first=Ali|title=Audio Interview: GUS G; \"The new album is going to be very diverse, a bit more mellow and a bit more classic rock-ish sounding.\"|url=http://metalshockfinland.com/2013/06/17/audio-interview-gus-g-the-new-album-is-going-to-be-very-diverse-a-bit-more-mellow-and-a-bit-more-classic-rockish-sounding/|publisher=Metal Shock Finland|accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=OZZY OSBOURNE/FIREWIND Guitarist GUS G. On Upcoming Solo Album - \"I'm Probably Going To Be Recording It Sometime In The Fall And Hopefully Can Release Early In 2014\"|url=http://www.bravewords.com/news/205865|publisher=Bravewords.com|accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===''Immortals''===\nIn July 2016, Firewind entered the studio to begin recording a new album. In November 2016, it was announced that the album, titled ''Immortals'', had been completed and would be released on January 20, 2017. On November 25, the band released the first single from this album, entitled \"Hands of Time\".<ref>{{cite web|title=FIREWIND: Release First Single From New Album \"Immortals\"|url=https://metalshockfinland.com/2016/11/25/firewind-release-first-single-from-new-album-immortals/|website=Metalshockfinland.com|accessdate=26 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n===''Lineup changes and self-titled album''===\nOn May 2019, it was announced by Gus G. that they will enter studio to start working on a follow-up to ''Immortals'' in August of that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://search.blabbermouth.net/news/firewind-to-enter-studio-this-summer/|title=FIREWIND To Enter Studio This Summer|date=May 17, 2019|website=Blabbermouth.net}}</ref> However, on 9 March 2020, it was announced that [[Bob Katsionis]] will be leaving the band in order to focus on his studio work and his other projects. They also parted ways with singer Henning Basse, because of personal reasons, which may prevent him from continuing with the band, with Herbie Langhans, who worked with [[Sinbreed]] and [[Avantasia]], replacing Basse on vocals. They also announced that the next album (with vocals finished by Langhans) will be released in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/firewind-announces-new-singer/|title=FIREWIND Announces New Singer|date=March 9, 2020|website=Blabbermouth.net|accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref> On 20 March 2020, the band premiered new single Rising Fire, which will be featured on the band's self-titled album, out on 15 May 2020.\n\n==Band members==\n{{BLP unsourced|date=April 2019}}\n===Current===\n* [[Gus G.]] \u2013 lead guitar, backing vocals (1998, 2002\u2013present), rhythm guitar, keyboards (1998, 2002\u20132004, 2020\u2013present), bass (1998)\n* [[Petros Christo]]doulidis \u2013 bass, backing vocals (2003\u2013present)\n* [[Johan Nunez]] \u2013 drums (2011\u2013present)\n* Herbie Langhans \u2013 lead vocals (2020\u2013present)\n\n===Touring members===\n====Lead vocals====\n* [[Mats Lev\u00e9n]] (2011)\n* Kelly Sundown Carpenter (2013\u20132015)\n\n===Former members===\n====Lead vocals====\n* Brandon Pender (1998)\n* [[Stephen Fredrick]] (2002-2004)\n* [[Chitral Somapala]] (2004-2006)\n* [[Apollo Papathanasio]] (2006-2013)\n* Henning Basse (2015\u20132020)\n\n====Guitar, keyboard and backing vocals====\n* [[Bob Katsionis]] (2004\u20132020)\n\n====Bass====\n* [[Kostas Exarhakis|Konstantine]] (2002-2003)\n\n====Drums====\n* [[Matt Scurfield]] (1998)\n* Brian Harris (2002-2003)\n* Stian Kristoffersen (2003-2006)\n* [[Mark Cross (musician)|Mark Cross]] (2006-2010)\n* Michael Ehr\u00e9 (2010-2011)\n\n====Recording timeline====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:99%;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10%;\"| Role\n! colspan=\"9\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Album\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:8%;\"| ''[[Between Heaven and Hell (album)|Between Heaven and Hell]]''<br /><small>(2002)</small>\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:8%;\"| ''[[Burning Earth]]''<br /><small>(2003)</small>\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:8%;\"| ''[[Forged by Fire]]''<br /><small>(2005)</small>\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:8%;\"| ''[[Allegiance (Firewind album)|Allegiance]]''<br /><small>(2006)</small>\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:8%;\"| ''[[The Premonition (album)|The Premonition]]''<br /><small>(2008)</small>\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:8%;\"| ''[[Days of Defiance]]''<br /><small>(2010)</small>\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:8%;\"| ''[[Few Against Many]]''<br /><small>(2012)</small>\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:8%;\"| ''[[Immortals (album)|Immortals]]''<br /><small>(2017)</small>\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:8%;\"|\nFirewind<br /><small>(2020)</small>\n|-\n!Lead Guitar\n|colspan=\"9\"|[[Gus G.]]\n|-\n!Vocals\n|colspan=\"2\"|[[Stephen Fredrick]]\n||[[Chitral Somapala]]\n|colspan=\"4\"|[[Apollo Papathanasio]]\n||Henning Basse\n||Herbie Langfors\n|-\n!Bass\n|[[Kostas Exarhakis|Konstantine]]\n|colspan=\"8\"|[[Petros Christo]]doulidis\n|-\n!Drums\n||Brian Harris\n|colspan=\"2\"|Stian Kristoffersen\n|colspan=\"3\"|[[Mark Cross (musician)|Mark Cross]]\n|colspan=\"3\"|[[Johan Nunez]]\n|-\n!Keyboards/Rhythm Guitar\n|colspan=\"2\"|[[Gus G.]]\n|colspan=\"6\"|[[Bob Katsionis]]\n|[[Gus G.]]\n|}\n\n===Timeline===\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:800 height:auto barincrement:20\nPlotArea = left:130 bottom:80 top:0 right:5\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat = mm/dd/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/1998 till:{{#time:m/d/Y}}\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:4\nScaleMajor = increment:3 start:1998\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:1998\nlegend = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:4\n\nColors =\n id:vocals  value:red         legend:Lead_vocals\n id:guitar  value:green       legend:Lead_guitar\n id:keys    value:purple      legend:Keyboards,_rhythm_guitar\n id:bass    value:blue        legend:Bass\n id:drums   value:orange      legend:Drums\n id:album   value:black       legend:Studio_album\n id:demos   value:gray(0.75)  legend:Demo\n\nLineData =\n layer:back color:album\n at:06/01/1998 color:demos\n at:07/30/2002\n at:11/11/2003\n at:01/05/2005\n at:07/10/2006\n at:03/21/2008\n at:10/25/2010\n at:05/21/2012\n at:01/20/2017\n\nBarData = \n bar:pender          text:\"Brandon Pender\"\n bar:fredrick        text:\"Stephen Fredrick\"\n bar:somapala        text:\"Chitral Somapala\"\n bar:papathanasio    text:\"Apollo Papathanasio\"\n bar:carpenter       text:\"Kelly Sundown Carpenter\"\n bar:basse           text:\"Henning Basse\"\n bar:herbie          text:\"Herbie Langhans\"\n bar:G               text:\"Gus G.\n bar:katsionis       text:\"Bob Katsionis\"\n bar:konstantine     text:\"Konstantine\"\n bar:christodoulidis text:\"Petros Christodoulidis\"\n bar:scurfield       text:\"Matt Scurfield\"\n bar:harris          text:\"Brian Harris\"\n bar:kristoffersen   text:\"Stian Landis Kristoffersen\"\n bar:cross           text:\"Mark Cross\"\n bar:ehr\u00e9            text:\"Michael Ehr\u00e9\"\n bar:nunez           text:\"Johan Nunez\